1.	Change password for both user and root account
a.	passwd command
2.	Disable login for root
a.	Make sure sysadmin is a sudoer
3.	Change root userâ€™s Shell in /etc/passwd from root:x:0:0:root:/root:/bin/bash
	to
	root:x:0:0:root:/root:/sbin/nologin
4.	Setup Firewall (These commands in this order will drop all incoming traffic except DNS and NTP. These will also allow all outgoing traffic.) *Note: only open port 80 on Ubuntu instead of 53 and 123
a.	iptables -P INPUT DROP 
iptables -P FORWARD DROP
iptables -P OUTPUT ACCEPT
iptables -L INPUT
iptables -A INPUT -p udp --dport 53 -j ACCEPT
iptables -A INPUT -p udp --dport 123 -j ACCEPT
sudo apt install iptables-persistent
5.	Forward syslog and rsyslog to splunk
a.	*.* @172.20.241.20 in /etc/rsyslog.conf file
6.	Update both Debian and Ubuntu Machinesa
a.	Sudo apt update
b.	Sudo apt upgrade
7.	Check users 
a.	Cat /etc/passwd
8.	Check /var/www/html on Ubuntu Web
9.	Remove write permissions
a.	chmod 0-w
10.	Check shadow file
a.	Sudo cat shadow
11.	Check sudoers
12.	Check cronjob
a.	Cat /etc/crontab
13.	Disable sshd
a.	Sudo systemctl disable ssh
14.	Make sure they have a default route configured
a.	Netstat -rn
15.	Backup etc folder
a.	sudo tar -cvzf etc_backup.tar.gz /etc
b.	sudo tar -xvzf etc_backup.tar.gz
16.	install Fail2Ban
a.	sudo apt install Fail2Ban
